    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/13479 introduced the `vim.opt` Lua API. It would be a small enhancement to add a `toggle()` method to boolean options to easily invert the value.\r\n\r\nCurrently to invert a value a bit of boilerplate is required, such as defining a function like:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n-- Toggle Boolean Options\r\n-- \tscope can be:\r\n-- \t\t• opt:        behaves like :set\r\n-- \t\t• opt_global: behaves like :setglobal\r\n-- \t\t• opt_local:  behaves like :setlocal\r\nlocal function toggle_opt(opt, scope)\r\n\tscope = scope or 'opt' -- use default if no scope passed\r\n\t-- type checking\r\n\tassert(type(vim[scope][opt]:get()) == 'boolean', 'Only booleans can be toggled!')\r\n\tvim[scope][opt] = not vim[scope][opt]:get() -- invert bool\r\nend\r\n\r\n-- Toggle spell checking\r\ntoggle_opt('spell', 'opt_local')\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nInverting bools could be much simpler with a `toggle()` method added to the `<metatable>` of boolean options, such as:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.opt_local.spell:toggle()\r\n```",
    "closed_at": "2023-09-20T21:18:48Z",
